Since the interest rate is compounded quarterly and we're calculating an annual rate, we will divide the yearly twelve months by the quarter three months.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Compounding period} &= \dfrac{12\text{ months}}{3\text{ months}}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{4}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, we will use the compounding period of 4.

Now, let's calculate each cash flow's present value and combine the values to determine the net present value in the fourth year.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{PV} &=\dfrac{\$815}{\left(1 + 0.093\right)^{1}}+\dfrac{\$990}{\left(1 + 0.093\right)^{2}}+\dfrac{\$0}{\left(1 + 0.093\right)^{3}}+\dfrac{\$1,520}{\left(1 + 0.093\right)^{4}}
\\[10pt]
&=\$ 745.65 +\$ 828.70 +\$0+\$ 1,065.03 
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$2,639.38}
\end{aligned}$$

**Based on our calculation, by computing each period's present value and combining each, the current value at the fourth year of the cash flows is $2,639.38.**
